[response] Let the given equation be
$$r = 2 \sin 4 \phi$$
We want to find the area of the region bounded by the lines $y = 0$ and $y = x$.

We can express the area as
$$A = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{r}{2} r \, d\phi \, d\theta = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{r^2}{2} \, d\phi \, d\theta$$
$$A = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{2\pi} r^2 \, d\phi \, d\theta = \frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \left[ \frac{r^3}{3} \right]_{0}^{2\pi} \, d\theta = \frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{(2\pi)^3}{3} \, d\theta = \frac{1}{2} \cdot \frac{8\pi^3}{3} \int_{0}^{2\pi} d\theta = \frac{4\pi^3}{3} \int_{0}^{2\pi} d\theta$$
$$A = \frac{4\pi^3}{3} [ \theta ]_{0}^{2\pi} = \frac{4\pi^3}{3} (2\pi - 0) = \frac{4\pi^3}{3} (2\pi) = \frac{8\pi^4}{3}$$
Thus, the area of the region is $\frac{8\pi^4}{3}$.

The area is
$$A = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{r^2}{2} \, d\phi \, d\theta = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{1}{2} \int_{0}^{2\pi} r^2 \, d\phi \, d\theta = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{1}{2} \left[ \frac{r^3}{3} \right]_{0}^{2\pi} d\theta = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{1}{2} \left( \frac{(2\pi)^3}{3} - 0 \right) d\theta = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{8\pi^3}{6} d\theta = \int_{0}^{2\pi} \frac{4\pi^3}{3} d\theta = \frac{4\pi^3}{3} \int_{0}^{2\pi} d\theta = \frac{4\pi^3}{3} (2\pi) = \frac{8\pi^4}{3}$$
Therefore, the area of the region bounded by the lines $y=0$ and $y=x$ is $\frac{8\pi^4}{3} \approx 7.556 \times 10^4$.

